#
# sprite-tool is a CLI tool for managing AI coding
# agents on sprites.dev — push plans, auto-
# checkpoint, monitor progress.  Authored by phiat
# (3 GH stars; described in README as "mad opus
# 4.6 porting speedrunning").  The Forth port at
# `ports/forth/sprite-tool.fs` is one of several
# implementations in the sprite-scripts repo
# (other ports include shell, Python, possibly
# Go).  Sister tools: sprite (the underlying
# sprites.dev CLI client), bd (Beads dependency
# tracker used internally).
#
# Critical extraction note: sprite-tool uses
# **Gforth stdlib `next-arg` primitive + hand-
# written matching** at sprite-tool.fs:468 et seq
# — corpus's **first documented Forth CLI
# pattern**.  Forth has NO FORMAL CLI PARSER
# LIBRARY in the stdlib — the language's
# philosophy is that every program builds the
# abstractions it needs from PRIMITIVES.
# `next-arg` is Gforth's argv-accessor primitive
# that returns `(addr len)` pairs on the stack
# (or `(0 0)` when exhausted); the caller writes
# the parsing logic by hand using `str=` for
# string comparison and stack operations for
# control flow.  Distinct from R272 C POSIX
# getopt (provides at least an option-string
# abstraction), R287 Nim parseopt (token
# iterator at language level), R311 Guile
# `(ice-9 getopt-long)` (full spec language).
# Forth's approach: LANGUAGE-AS-LIBRARY — the
# CLI parser IS the application code.  Extends
# cross-language CLI taxonomy to FIFTY-SIX
# library variants: Rust (6), Go (4),
# Python (3), Crystal 1 OptionParser (R269),
# Haskell (R270), OCaml (R271), C (R272),
# Java (R276), Kotlin (R277), Scala (R278),
# Dart (R279), Ruby (R280), Perl (R281),
# PHP (R282), Swift (R283), F# (R284),
# Lua (R285), C# (R286), Nim 1 parseopt (R287),
# Zig (R288), D (R289), Racket (R290),
# Common Lisp 1 (R291), Erlang (R292),
# Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294), Common
# Lisp 2 clingon (R295), Julia (R296), SWI-
# Prolog optparse (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298),
# Crystal 2 Admiral (R299), V stdlib `flag`
# (R300), Nim 2 cligen (R301), Clojure babashka.
# cli (R302), Gleam Glint (R303), Ada GNAT.
# Command_Line (R304), C++ 1 CLI11 (R305),
# Elixir Optimus (R306), Vala GLib.OptionContext
# (R307), Hare stdlib getopt (R308), Standard ML
# stdlib GetOpt (R309), Fortran M_CLI2 (R310),
# Guile (ice-9 getopt-long) (R311), Free Pascal
# TCustomApplication (R312), Idris 2 System.
# GetOpts (R313), Mercury stdlib getopt_io
# (R314), Eiffel Gobo AP_PARSER (R315), C++ 2
# boost::program_options (R316), **Forth/Gforth
# `next-arg`** (R317 — NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN
# MILESTONE**: 56 cross-language CLI library
# variants documented.  Forth joins the taxonomy
# as one of the OLDEST languages still in use
# (Chuck Moore, 1968) with the MOST MINIMAL CLI
# handling — language-as-library where the
# parser IS the application code.
#
# Critical extraction note: sprite-tool uses
# **Forth handwritten-stack-string-equality
# matching** at sprite-tool.fs:477-481, 500-516,
# 949-957 — `2dup s" --help" str= if 2drop ...
# then` is the canonical pattern.  `s" ..."`
# creates an `(addr len)` pair on the stack;
# `str=` compares two `(addr len)` strings on the
# stack and pushes a Forth flag (true/false).
# `2dup` duplicates the top 2 cells (preserving
# the arg-string for next match), `2drop` cleans
# them when matched.  Distinct from R272 C POSIX
# getopt (option-string parsed internally), R311
# Guile `getopt-long` spec, R307 Vala GLib
# OptionEntry table.  Forth's approach: HAND-
# WRITTEN STRING-EQUALITY MATCHING — caller
# writes the matching code explicitly using stack
# operations.  Corpus's **first documented
# handwritten-stack-string-equality CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: sprite-tool uses
# **Forth nested `then`-chains for flag dispatch**
# at sprite-tool.fs:500-516 — DEEPLY NESTED
# `else 2dup s"...";  str= if ... else 2dup ...`
# chain.  Forth has no `match`/`case` for strings,
# so each flag becomes ANOTHER nested `if ...
# else ... then` arm.  Each `then` CLOSES one
# `if`-`else`.  Distinct from R313 Idris 2 ADT
# pattern-match, R290 Racket `match`, R311 Guile
# `case`/`cond`, R314 Mercury `;`-separated
# Prolog clauses.  Forth's approach: NESTED-
# `then` CHAINS — corpus's **first documented
# nested-if-chain CLI dispatch pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: sprite-tool uses
# **Gforth `{ var }` local-variable syntax** at
# sprite-tool.fs:490, 493 — `0 { idx }` and
# `true { parsing }` declare locals bound to the
# top-of-stack value.  `to idx` STORES a new
# value to the local.  Distinct from `variable
# VAR` / `VAR !` (Forth global variable + `!`
# store) — locals are scoped to the word, globals
# are module-level.  Sister to R311 Guile `(let
# ((var value)) ...)` (lexical bindings) but
# Gforth locals have RPN syntax.  Corpus's **first
# documented Gforth-locals-`{ }`-syntax CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: sprite-tool uses
# **Forth handwritten `." ... "` usage text** at
# sprite-tool.fs:391-446 — HELP TEXT generation
# via inline `." text" cr` STRING-OUTPUT-LITERAL.
# Forth's `." text"` is a COMPILE-TIME-STRING +
# PRINT-WORD combined token; `cr` prints carriage
# return.  No `--help` auto-generation because
# there's no formal spec to generate from —
# each usage block is hand-written.  Distinct
# from R310 Fortran M_CLI2 (help_text passed as
# array to set_args), R311 Guile `usageInfo`
# helper, R313 Idris 2 `usageInfo` helper.
# Forth's approach: HANDWRITTEN HELP via
# successive `." ... " cr` calls.  Corpus's
# **first documented handwritten-`."`-help CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: sprite-tool uses
# **Forth fall-through-top-level invocation** at
# sprite-tool.fs:966 — `main bye` at the FILE
# BOTTOM invokes the `main` word then calls
# `bye` to exit Gforth.  Forth files are
# INTERPRETED LINEARLY — when Gforth reaches
# `main bye`, it RUNS those words immediately.
# Distinct from R311 Guile (must `(main args)`
# inside `(define (main ...))`), R313 Idris 2
# `main : IO ()` (IO monad), R310 Fortran
# `program iapwscli` (named program block),
# R305 C++ `int main(int argc, char** argv)`
# (formal main function).  Forth's approach:
# NO MAIN FUNCTION — the entire script is just
# words; the LAST WORDS in the file ARE the
# entry-point invocation.  Corpus's **first
# documented fall-through-top-level CLI
# invocation pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: sprite-tool uses
# **Forth `s"..."  str=` literal-string-on-stack
# pattern** at sprite-tool.fs:477-481, 500-516 —
# `s" --help"` is a COMPILE-TIME STRING LITERAL
# that pushes `(addr len)` onto the stack at
# runtime.  Distinct from R272 C `"..."` (C
# string literal — null-terminated), R270 Haskell
# `"..."` (immutable String type), R313 Idris 2
# `"..."` (typed String literal).  Forth's
# approach: STRING-AS-STACK-PAIR — each string is
# TWO stack cells `(address, length)` rather than
# a pointer or boxed value.  This is the
# QUINTESSENTIAL Forth string convention,
# affecting how every CLI matching operation is
# expressed.  Corpus's **first documented
# `(addr, len)`-stack-pair string CLI pattern**.
